DATS 6101 Project 1

Tyler Wallett, Anushka Vuppala and David Li

2022-10-24

Our research topic aims to perform explorartory data analysis on the Nearest Earth Objects (NEO) dataset recorded by NASA. This particular dataset includes thousands of labeled observations, over the last 22 years, across multiple attributes that each aim to describe a specific object. Borrowing from the humor of the recent film Dont Look Up by Adam Mckay and NASAs success in the Double Asteroid Redirection Test (DART) mission, we thought that further describing and exploring this dataset would be opportune.

Lets find the mode

getmode <- function(v) {
   uniqv <- unique(v)
   uniqv[which.max(tabulate(match(v, uniqv)))]
}

Outliers

Removing outliers is a good way to clean the dataset and obtain correct results. To remove the outliers in the dataset, we shall use outlierKD2 function

hazardous_outlier_removed = na.omit(outlierKD2(hazardous,absolute_magnitude, qqplt=TRUE, rm=TRUE))

## Proportion (%) of outliers: 2.7

non_hazardous_outlier_removed = na.omit(outlierKD2(non_hazardous,absolute_magnitude, qqplt=TRUE, rm=TRUE))

Distinct Values

Now, there are multiple asteroids with the same id and name in the dataset. Each of those asteroids with the same name have the same absolute magnitude. We shall remove these in order for the dataset to follow the rules of a relational dataset. We use the group_by function provided in R to do so and we take the mean of those asteroids with the same id and name so we dont have any risk of losing the data.

hazardous_grouped = hazardous_outlier_removed %>% group_by(name) %>% summarise(absolute_magnitude = mean(absolute_magnitude))

The dimension of the hazardous dataframe after using only distinct asteroid IDs => 2105, 2

non_hazardous_grouped = non_hazardous_outlier_removed %>% group_by(name) %>% summarise(absolute_magnitude = mean(absolute_magnitude))

The dimension of the non_hazardous dataframe after using only distinct asteroid IDs => 25098, 2

Now, with all outliers removed and distinct values extracted, we can perform t-tests.

Anova Test:

For anova test, we need 2 samples of equal size - one from hazardous and another from non-hazardous

# creating a third column in both dataframes to account for categorical variable - hazardous
non_hazardous_grouped$hazardous=0
hazardous_grouped$hazardous=1
non_hazardous_sample = sample(1:nrow(non_hazardous_grouped), size=2105)
summary(aov(absolute_magnitude ~ hazardous, data=rbind(hazardous_grouped, non_hazardous_sample)))
##               Df   Sum Sq  Mean Sq  F value Pr(>F)    
## hazardous      1 36110958 36110958 24899010 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   2104     3051        1                    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Observation - the p-value is a small number (<0.001) which indicates that we can reject the null hypothesis and confirm that the mean for hazardous and non-hazardous NEOs is not the same. Note that the p-value is same from results obtained in anova test and t-test.

Correlation Plots:

A correlation plot is used to determine how close each variable is to the other. Here, we are noting down the correlation between the 5 numerical variables in our NEO dataset.

library(corrplot)
corrplot(cor(hazardous %>% select(absolute_magnitude, miss_distance, relative_velocity, est_diameter_max, est_diameter_min)), method="number")

As noted in the above correlation plot, we see that the the min and max estimated diameter is closely related to the absolute magnitude. It is inversely related. This makes sense because absolute magnitude (brightness of a NEO) indicates the size of the asteroid in question. And hence, we can say that the bigger the size of the asteroid, lesser the absolute magnitude (brighter the star), and thus potentially more hazardous is the asteroid. All other variables fall below the threshold limit.
